BrendaPopplewell 2025-01-02 05:37 p.m.
Your Honor, and may it please the court,

3 MSC 8217 allows the Attorney General to arbitrate lawsuits filed against the government and its employees.

Every day, government employees, like Catonius, are sued. But only a scintilla of these lawsuits ever actually reach the courts. Indeed, the Attorney General uses his 8217 arbitration power to unilaterally "adjudicate" these cases--awarding hundredes of thousands of dollars in damages against employees, including Catonius, without the benefit of a judicial trial.
And these damages are not paid by the public fisc, but by the employees themselves.

This practice is unconstitutional. When sued for legal damages or for torts resembling common-law causes of action, the Due Process Clause guarantees government employees the right to a judicial trial before being subject to any kind of deprivation. Nonetheless, Catonius and other employees are afforded no judicial trial and forced to pay up or face criminal charges.

The Judicial Power Clause of the Mayflower Constitution likewise bolsters this right. That Clause prohibits the government from withdrawing actions from judicial cognizance and handing them over to the executive branch for an "in-house trial."

Additionally, we've sufficiently demonstrated the prerequisites for preliminary relief in this case and pray that the Court issue an injunction without delay.

singhski 2025-01-02 06:47 p.m.
Your Honor, and may it please the court,

Plaintiff makes the argument that 8217's arbitration mechanism violates the Due Process Clause. Due process is not a one-size-fits all requirement. In fact, the very essence of due process is to be heard "at a meaningful time and in a meaningful manner." Armstrong v. Manzo, 380 U. S. 545, 380 U. S. 552 (1965). Here, employees like Catonius are provided notice, an opportunity to present evidence, and access to review mechanisms.

Moreover,"[b]y agreeing to arbitrate a statutory claim, a party does not forgo the substantive rights afforded by the statute; it only submits to their resolution in an arbitral, rather than a judicial, forum." Gilmer v. Interstate/Johnson Lane Corp., 500 U.S. 20, 26 (1991). Plaintiff argues that arbitration under 8217 may violate due process by denying employees like Catonius a judicial trial. This goes against the spirit of Gilmer entirely, as it affirms that arbitration does not eliminate the rights afforded by the statute, they are simply being resolved in a different forum. The arbitrator still addresses the substance of the claims, but within the framework set forth by 8217. When the forum is fair, it is consistent with constitutional principles.

"Mere injuries, however substantial, in terms of money, time and energy necessarily expended in the absence of a stay, are not enough. The possibility that adequate compensatory or other corrective relief will be available at a later date, in the ordinary course of litigation, weighs heavily against a claim of irreparable harm." Sampson v. Murray, 415 U.S. 61, 90 (1974). The irreparable harm requirement is unreachable. Catonius and other employees can seek judicial review of arbitration orders.(edited)
singhski 2025-01-02 06:47 p.m.
Plaintiff makes a good argument that the Judicial Power Clause prohibits the government from withdrawing actions from judicial cognizance and handing them over to the executive branch for an "in-house trial" what the Plaintiff conspicuously omits however, is that arbiters, who handle the arbitration, are completely untied to the executive branch. They are completely impartial and provide a fair forum to claimants and respondents.

BrendaPopplewell 2025-01-02 07:56 p.m.
Your Honor, and may it please the Court,

The Attorney General makes multiple wrong assertions.

First, he argues that providing employees a non-judicial hearing is consistent with the guarantees of the Due Process Clause.

In SEC v. Jarkesy, 603 U.S. __ (2024), the Supreme Court rejected this theory. The majority in Jarkesy held that cases concerning private rights (i.e., cases between individuals) must be adjudicated by Article III courts:

"We have repeatedly explained that matters concerning private rights may not be removed from Article III courts. A hallmark that we have looked to in determining if a suit concerns private rights is whether it is made of the stuff of the traditional actions at common law tried by the courts at Westminster in 1789. If a suit is in the nature of an action at common law, then the matter presumptively concerns private rights, and adjudication by an Article III court is mandatory."

Slip op. at 14 (citations omitted.)

At the same time, Jarkesy recognized that cases concerning public rights (i.e., cases against the government) can, and historically have been, adjudicated by the executive branch in agency tribunals. But aside from this exception, all traditional legal claims, including the ones against Catonius, have to be adjudicated by Article III courts. E.g. slip op. at 19 ("[T]raditional legal claims must be decided by courts, whether they originate in a newly fashioned regulatory scheme or possess a long line of common-law forebears.")

The Jarkesy majority did not reach the question of whether the SEC's civil penalty scheme implicated due process; but Gorsuch's concurring opinion does:
BrendaPopplewell 2025-01-02 07:56 p.m.
"[W]ere there any doubt, the Due Process Clause con- firms these conclusions. Cf. Murrays Lessee, 18 How., at 275 (explaining that the Article III challenge before the Court could best be considered as raising a due process question). Because the penalty the SEC seeks would depriv[e] Mr. Jarkesy of property, Amdt. 5, due process demands nothing less than the process and proceedings of the common law, 3 Story 1783, at 661. That means the regular course of trial proceedings with their usual protec- tions, see Murrays Lessee, 18 How., at 280, not the use of ad hoc adjudication procedures before the same agency re- sponsible for prosecuting the law, subject only to hands-off judicial review, see supra, at 1011."
BrendaPopplewell 2025-01-02 07:58 p.m.
Second, the violation of due process is irreparable injury because it is a violation of a constitutional right.


Third, State law provides that arbitration orders are "final" and "unappealable." There's no venue for judicial review.

And fourth, all arbitrations are made by the Attorney General or his "designees" pursuant to State law. So the Attorney General's claims that his arbitrators are independent from the executive branch is false. They are his designees. They act by and through his authority; they are no better than the Attorney General in the flesh.
BrendaPopplewell 2025-01-02 07:59 p.m.
Also, Gilmer v. Johnson Lane Corp. does not touch the issue of due process. It's a statutory interpretation case.

singhski 2025-01-03 12:14 p.m.
Employees are given formal notice of the claims against them as part of the arbitration process initiated, this is done through adding them to the arbitration ticket. The statute does not explicitly detail the procedural mechanics, but in practice, the arbitration process allows the employee/his or her counsel (the Solicitor General) to present evidence, make arguments, and submit relevant documentation to support their defense.

Although 8217(b) makes certain arbitration decisions final and unappealable, employees can still pursue limited judicial review if there are claims of procedural irregularities, constitutional violations, or excess of authority during the arbitration process.

Arbitration's due process hinges on the adequacy of the proceedings. This standard is the same as court proceedings, should a court proceeding be inconsistent with the spirit of due process, the affected party can always appeal the decision on those grounds.

But what we also must remember is that suits against agents are de facto suits against the government, which is where the finality from 8217b stems from. When the AG finds in favor of the plaintiff and awards relief, the government is essentially admitting liability and resolving the claim on behalf of its employee. So, if the government isn't awarding relief out of its own pocket, that is a procedural error, and an error that can be fixed by legislation rather than axing the entire process.

So, it's more of a matter that it's hard to appeal the order due to the finality clause of 8217, but it's not impossible when suing the DOJ on pretenses of due process deficiencies as the plaintiff is doing now.

The Court finds that Plaintiff is likely to succeed on the merits of his Due Process claim. There is no dispute that Plaintiff was deprived of his property by the confiscation of the sign. The Court also considers the Mathews test, and finds that the procedures used were not constitutionally sufficient.

IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that Defendants return Plaintiff's sign to his property by no later than 8:00 a.m. on June 10, 2018

Because Catonius' right to due process has been violated, and continues to be violated for as long as he remains deprived of his property, and only on that ground, we move the Court to reconsider its ruling as to our request for equitable disgorgement.
